<asp:Content ID="Content1" ContentPlaceHolderID="ContentPlaceHolder1" runat="server">
    <p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>Dear Dad<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>You may remember about a year ago I told you something about science that 
    fascinated me and that I thought would fascinate you.&nbsp; But all you said in 
    reply was “puh, how do they know that?!” and I went away feeling very 
    disappointed.&nbsp; Now, it may have taken me a year to get around to it but I 
    have tried here to explain to you in layman’s terms exactly how science enables 
    us to work this out.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>It’s taken me an hour to write it so please read it!&nbsp; And let me know 
    if you have any questions or if you wonder about how anything is derived or 
    measured.&nbsp; The main purpose of this is not to get the figures dead right (I 
    can’t as I don’t know all the exact numbers) but rather to demonstrate the way 
    that science does allow us to calculate such amazing things.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>I’m only writing this because I want you to catch a glimpse of, and be 
    inspired by, the power of science.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    &nbsp;</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <b><span>Feynman’s Claim<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>The electromagnetic force is very strong and is made up of positive and 
    negative charges.&nbsp; Normally these charges turn up in equal proportion which 
    means that the net charge in a given object is zero.&nbsp; Richard Feynman 
    claimed that if two people stood at arms’ length and one had only 99% of the 
    charge that the other had then the force between them would be enough to lift 
    the ‘weight’ of the earth.&nbsp; Here are my simple calculations to show how 
    this can be calculated.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <b><span>How much force is required to lift the ‘weight’ of the earth?<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>The first thing we will need is the mass of the earth.&nbsp; We can work 
    this out quite accurately by dropping an object of a known weight and seeing how 
    fast it accelerates.&nbsp; Scientists have found that the earth has a mass of 
    approximately:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>Mass of Earth = 6,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000 kgs<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>Now we need to work out the force required to lift this mass.&nbsp; Isaac 
    Newton defined Force to be equal to mass times acceleration:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
    F = ma<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>When we weigh things on the Earth we are measuring their mass multiplied 
    by the acceleration due to gravity at the Earth’s surface which is 9.8 metres 
    per second<sup> </sup>per second (that is, every second the velocity increases 
    by 9.8 metres per second).&nbsp;&nbsp; For the sake of this exercise let’s round 
    it up to 10 metres per second per second instead.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>Therefore, the force required to ‘lift’ the earth is:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>F = 6,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000 * 10 = 
    60,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000 Newtons<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <b><span>What is the electric charge of a human being?<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>We either need to know how many electrons (negative) or how many protons 
    (positive) there are in a human body.&nbsp;&nbsp; If a person is neutrally 
    ‘charged’ then they will have equal numbers of electrons and protons.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>To work this out I guessed the masses of the main elements we are made out 
    of (hydrogen, carbon, oxygen etc) and then multiplied by the numbers of 
    electrons in each of those elements.&nbsp; I assumed that an average human is 
    made up of about 80kgs of matter.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>By my calculations (and checking on the internet with other people’s 
    calculations) I think we have 24,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000 electrons 
    in our bodies.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>The charge due to a single electron is defined to be 
    0.00000000000000000016 Coulombs.&nbsp; So, for all the electrons in a human body 
    we find the total electric charge for a human being to be:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>Charge on a Neutral Human Being&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
    3,840,000,000 Coulombs<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>We now need to work out the charge on the other human who has 1% less 
    charge.&nbsp; In other words, multiply it by 0.99:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>Charged Human Being&nbsp;&nbsp; 3,840,000,000 x 0.99 = 3,801,600,000 
    Coulombs<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <b><span>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <b><span>What is the force between the two humans?<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>The force between any two objects is given by Coulomb’s Law which states:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span><!--[if gte vml 1]>
