<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
    R is the distance between the two objects<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
    Q1 is the charge on the first object<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
    Q2 is the charge on the second object<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
    K is the Electric Force constant which is needed to get everything in the 
    correct units<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>&nbsp;<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>We have already worked out the two charges on the humans, Q1 and Q2.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>R is the distance in metres between them.&nbsp; The problem says “arm’s 
    length” so let’s call it one metre.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>That just leaves the value of K which is:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
    k = 8987551787<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>So the force between the two humans is:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span><!--[if gte vml 1]>
    <v:shape
 id="yiv482043181_x005f_x0000_i1026" o:spid="_x0000_i1026" type="#_x0000_t75"
 alt="" style='width:225pt;height:27pt'>
    <v:imagedata src="file:///C:\Users\HewittM\AppData\Local\Temp\msohtmlclip1\01\clip_image002.gif"
  o:href="cid:image002.png@01CDCBE5.A4397270" 
        xmlns:v="urn:schemas-microsoft-com:vml"/>
    </v:shape>
    <![endif]--><![if !vml]>
    <img border="0" height="36" 
        src="file:///C:/Users/HewittM/AppData/Local/Temp/msohtmlclip1/01/clip_image002.gif" 
        v:shapes="yiv482043181_x005f_x0000_i1026" width="300" /><![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>Which equals about 131,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000 Newtons.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>These very rough calculations show that the force in question is enough to 
    lift about 20,000 earths!
    <o:p>
    </o:p>
    </span>
</p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>The main point is not that the figures are exactly right but that science, 
    using very simple maths and very simple logic, can work out such magnificent 
    facts.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
<p class="MsoNormal">
    <span>QED(ish)!<o:p></o:p></span></p>
